post_text:
CUHSD's Haydee Rodriguez Has been appointed by Governor Newsom to the State Board of Education. We are so proud of her!

"Haydee Rodriguez, 53, of El Centro, has been appointed to the State Board of Education. Rodriguez has been a teacher at Central Union High School since 1998 and currently serves as the Advancement Via Individual Determination (AVID) coordinator. She earned a Master of Arts degree in education from Stanford University. This position requires Senate confirmation and the compensation is $100 per diem. Rodriguez is a Democrat."

Today is Juneteenth, the day the news President Lincoln has abolished slavery reached Texas when federal troops arrived to make sure all were set free.

Today, we are still facing racism in our country. The more we know about each other, the more we are tolerant and caring.

Know your history: https://www.history.com/news/what-is-juneteenth

post_text:
With the resignation of Mr. Todd Evangelist on March 13, 2020 the Central Union High School District has a vacancy on the 5-member board. The Governing Board has two options: first the trustees may appoint a qualified candidate to fill the vacancy until the next election or second the trustees may take no action and leave the seat vacant until the November election.

The Governing Board is accepting letters of interested from individuals that are willing to serving from May to November 2020. Interested parties should submit a letter of interest to the District no later than May 8, 2020 at 5:00 PM to be considered. Click here for more information: http://www.cuhsd.net/Board-of-Trustees/Board-Members/index.html

post_text:
In an effort to provide hope and support to our community and students with a message that we care about them, we miss them, and we honor them, we will turn our Stadium Lights on each Friday from 8 to 9 pm on April 24, May 1, 8, 15, 22 and 29th.

Around the country, communities are celebrating and showing support with nightly events for health care workers along with, grocery workers, law enforcement and other essential workers. Others in our community have re-hung their holiday lights and turned them on nightly for the same reasons. Hotels and high-rise buildings use their lights for messages of support. Drawing inspiration from the National Porch Light Campaign and others, we will turn our biggest lights on to celebrate our community and show solidarity that we are together. We miss our students and look forward to returning to campus.
text:
In an effort to provide hope and support to our community and students with a message that we care about them, we miss them, and we honor them, we will turn our Stadium Lights on each Friday from 8 to 9 pm on April 24, May 1, 8, 15, 22 and 29th.

Around the country, communities are celebrating and showing support with nightly events for health care workers along with, grocery workers, law enforcement and other essential workers. Others in our community have re-hung their holiday lights and turned them on nightly for the same reasons. Hotels and high-rise buildings use their lights for messages of support. Drawing inspiration from the National Porch Light Campaign and others, we will turn our biggest lights on to celebrate our community and show solidarity that we are together. We miss our students and look forward to returning to campus.

While this means our school facilities won’t be physically open for students, THE SCHOOL YEAR IS NOT OVER!

Distance Learning is happening at all CUHSD schools online. If you need help with a device or connecting to a teacher, please contact your school.

Visit the district webpage to see the press release from ICOE at www.cuhsd.net

All District Office and Schools Closed to the Public Beginning March 20, 2020

In accordance the Governor Newsom’s Stay Home Order issued on March 19, 2020 (N-33-20), the Central Union High School District and all its schools and office are closed to the public effective March 20, 2020. Only essential employees are working on site to ensure the delivery of essential services. Many other employees are working remotely.

If you need to contact someone in the school district, please use the Staff Directory function located on the top banner of our web page.

As of March 11 at 5:55 PM, there are now two presumptive positive cases of COVID-19 in Imperial County. None of them are students or staff at any of our schools. As of now, we are proceeding with all classes, extra curricular events and small meetings until futher notice.

We are in regular communication with the IC Public Health Department , and Imperial County Office of Education for the most recent information and direction. Please see our web-page for links to Public Offices.

CUHSD will issue more information as soon as it is available.

Visit the Imperial County Public Health Department for local information

March 4 at 5:36 PM ·

Imperial County Schools are gearing up for the first Anti-Vaping community event at Southwest High School on March 11. Partnering with local agencies, they hope to increase the awareness, education, and action in the area of anti-vaping. Vaping is an epidemic for our youth.

Join us to learn more about the dangerous health effects of vaping.
